res: Insights From the Literary World -- tFive Urban studies and urban ideologies -- t21 The “Urban Age” in Question -- t22 What Role For Social Science in the “Urban Age”? -- t23 City as Ideology -- t24 Urbanizing Urban Political Ecology: A Critique of Methodological Cityism -- t25 Whither Urban Studies? -- tSIX Visualizations— ideologies and experiments -- t26 A Typology of Urban Switzerland -- t27 Is the Mediterranean Urban? -- t28 Visualizing an Urbanized Planet— Materials -- tSEVEN Political strate gies, struggles and horizons -- t29 Two Approaches to “World Management”: C. A. Doxiadis and R. B. Fuller -- t30 City Becoming World: Nancy, Lefebvre and the Global-Urban Imagination -- t31 The Right to the City and Beyond: Notes on a Lefebvrian Reconceptualization -- t32 The Hypertrophic City Versus the Planet of Fields -- t33 Becoming Urban: On Whose Terms? -- tCoda -- t34 Dissolving City, Planetary Metamorphosis -- tContributors -- tSources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a1970 formulierte Henri Lefebvre seine radikale These der vollkommenen Urbanisierung der Gesellschaft, eine Entwicklung, die seiner Meinung nach den radikalen Umschwung von einer Analyse der Stadtformen zur Untersuchung von Urbanisierungsprozessen erforderte.Indem es klassische und zeitgenössische Texte zur “Urbanisierungsfrage” zusammenführt, untersucht dieses Buch verschiedene theoretische, erkenntnistheoretische, methodologische und politische Schlussfolgerungen aus Lefebvres These. Es versammelt eine Reihe von analytischen und kartografischen Interventionen, die traditionelle Raumontologien ablösen (städtisch/ländlich, Stadt/Land, Stadt/Nicht-Stadt, Gesellschaft/Natur), um die heterogenen Implosionen und Explosionen der vom Kapitalismus bestimmten Urbanisierung über Orte, Regionen, Territorien, Kontinente und Ozeane hinweg bis in planetare Größenordnungen hinein zu untersuchen.  aIn 1970, Henri Lefebvre put forward the radical hypothesis of the complete urbanization of society, a circumstance that in his view required a radical shift from the analysis of urban form to the investigation of urbanization processes. Drawing together classic and contemporary texts on the “urbanization question”, this book explores various theoretical, epistemological, methodological and political implications of Lefebvre’s hypothesis. It assembles a series of analytical and cartographic interventions that supersede inherited spatial ontologies (urban/rural, town/country, city/non-city, society/nature) in order to investigate the uneven implosions and explosions of capitalist urbanization across places, regions, territories, continents and oceans up to the planetary scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aArchitektur. 4aGesellschaftswissenschaftler. 4aSoziologie. 4aUrbanismus. 4aÖkonomie. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  aArchitektur.  aSoziologie.  aUrbanismus.  aÖkonomie.1 aAjl, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngelo, Hillary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, Neil , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrenner, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedmann, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGandy, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleeson, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoonewardena, Kanishka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanai, J. Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatsikis, Nik